xxl.cursors
Interface Cursor

All Known Subinterfaces:
Join, Sorter
All Known Implementing Classes:
AbstractCursor, Aggregator, ArrayCursor, BufferedCursor, DecoratorCursor, EmptyCursor, Enumerator, Grouper, IteratorCursor, Mapper, PeekIteratorCursor, Repeater, ReplacementSelection, WhileDropper, WhileTaker, HashGrouper, Sequentializer, EnumerationCursor, Merger, ResultSetCursor
public interface Cursor
extends PeekIterator

The interface Cursor extends the interface PeekIterator.

Additional functionality is: update(), close() and reset().
General contract:
If an Exception is thrown by a Cursor consequent calls to methods are not guarantied to produce correct results.

See Also:
Iterator, PeekIterator

Method Detail

close

public void close()
Closes the Cursor. Signals the cursor to cleanup resources, close files, etc.
After a call to close() calls to methods like next() or peek() are not guarantied to yield proper results.
Multiple calls to close() do not have any effect, i.e. if close() was called the Cursor remains in the state "closed".

public boolean hasNext()
Returns true if the iteration has more elements. (In other words, returns true if next or peek would return an element rather than throwing an exception.)

peek

public Object peek()
            throws NoSuchElementException,
                   UnsupportedOperationException
Shows the next element in the iteration without removing it from the underlying collection.
But be aware that an implementation of this method uses a kind of buffer-strategy, therefore it is possible that the returned element will be removed from the underlying collection, e.g. the caller can use an instance of a Cursor depending on an Iterator, so the next element returned by a call to peek will be removed, when an Iterator does not support the peek-method and it has to be buffered, if this functionality should be supported. (optional operation)
Specified by:
peek in interface PeekIterator
Returns:
the next element in the iteration.
Throws:
NoSuchElementException - iteration has no more elements.
UnsupportedOperationException - if the peek operation is not supported by this Cursor.

remove

public void remove()
            throws IllegalStateException,
                   UnsupportedOperationException
Removes from the underlying collection the last element returned by the Cursor. (optional operation)
This method can be called only once per call to next or peek. The behavior of a Cursor is unspecified if the underlying collection is modified while the iteration is in progress in any way other than by calling this method.
Specified by:
remove in interface PeekIterator
Throws:
UnsupportedOperationException - if the remove operation is not supported by this Cursor.
IllegalStateException - if the next or peek method has not yet been called, or the remove method has already been called after the last call to the next or peek method.

reset

public void reset()
           throws UnsupportedOperationException
Resets the Cursor to its initial state. (optional operation)
So the caller is able to traverse the underlying collection again. The modifications, removes and updates concerning the underlying collection, are still persistent.
Throws:
UnsupportedOperationException - if the reset method is not supported by the Cursor.

supportsPeek

public boolean supportsPeek()
Returns true if the peek-operation is supported by this Cursor. Else returns false.
Specified by:
supportsPeek in interface PeekIterator
Returns:
true if the peek operation is supported by this Cursor.

update

public void update(Object object)
            throws IllegalStateException,
                   UnsupportedOperationException
Replaces the object that was returned by the last call to next or peek. (optional operation)
This operation must not be called after a call to hasNext. It should follow a call to next or peek. This method should be called only once per call to next or peek.
The behavior of a Cursor is unspecified if the underlying collection is modified while the iteration is in progress in any way other than by calling this method.
Note, that this operation is optional and might not work for all cursors.
Parameters:
object - the object that replaces the object returned by the last call to next or peek.
Throws:
IllegalStateException - if there is no object which can be updated.
UnsupportedOperationException - if the update operation is not supported by the Cursor.
